  "text": "The Envoy xDS Aggregated Discovery Service (ADS) gRPC server is implemented across multiple C++ source files in the envoyproxy/envoy repository. The implementation consists of the following key components:\n\n## gRPC Stream Handler\nThe gRPC bidirectional streaming is handled by the `GrpcStream` template class in `source/extensions/config_subscription/grpc/grpc_stream.h`. This class manages the connection to the xDS management server, handles message sending/receiving, and implements backoff/retry logic. The `GrpcMuxFailover` class in `grpc_mux_failover.h` provides failover support for primary and secondary xDS sources.\n\n## Main ADS Multiplexer Implementation\nThe core ADS implementation is provided by multiple versions:\n\n1. **Legacy Implementation** (`grpc_mux_impl.h/cc`): The original ADS API implementation that multiplexes multiple resource types (EDS, CDS, RDS, LDS, etc.) over a single gRPC stream. Key methods include:\n   - `addWatch()`: Adds subscriptions to resources\n   - `onDiscoveryResponse()`: Handles responses from the server\n   - `sendDiscoveryRequest()`: Sends subscription requests to the server\n\n2. **Template-based Implementation** (`xds_mux/grpc_mux_impl.h/cc`): A generic template-based implementation with variants:\n   - `GrpcMuxDelta`: Uses delta-xDS protocol (DeltaDiscoveryRequest/Response)\n   - `GrpcMuxSotw`: Uses state-of-the-world protocol (DiscoveryRequest/Response)\n\n3. **Newer Implementation** (`new_grpc_mux_impl.h/cc`): An updated implementation with improved resource management.\n\n## Resource Subscription Tracking\nThe `WatchMap` class (`watch_map.h/cc`) manages subscriptions to xDS resources. It:\n- Multiplexes multiple watchers (subscribers) interested in the same resources\n- Tracks which resource names should be added/removed from the subscription\n- Delivers updates to all interested watches\n- Maintains a reference count of resource interests\n\n## Delta-xDS State Machine\nThe `DeltaSubscriptionState` class (`xds_mux/delta_subscription_state.h/cc`) implements the delta-xDS protocol state machine. It:\n- Tracks per-resource versions for efficient delta updates\n- Manages subscription interest changes (resource additions/removals)\n- Handles resource TTL/heartbeat mechanism\n- Generates appropriate DeltaDiscoveryRequest messages\n\n## State-of-the-World (SoTW) Subscription State\nThe `SotwSubscriptionState` class (`xds_mux/sotw_subscription_state.h/cc`) implements the traditional state-of-the-world xDS protocol. It:\n- Maintains version_info and nonce from responses\n- Generates DiscoveryRequest messages\n- Handles full resource set updates\n\n## ACK/NACK Processing\nThe ACK/NACK mechanism is handled through:\n\n1. **UpdateAck Structure** (`update_ack.h`): Contains nonce, type_url, and error_detail fields for acknowledging or negatively acknowledging resource updates.\n\n2. **PausableAckQueue** (`pausable_ack_queue.h/cc`): A queue that manages ACKs/NACKs with support for pausing specific resource types. This solves head-of-line blocking issues in ADS by allowing paused resource types to not block other types.\n\n3. **BaseSubscriptionState ACK Methods** (`xds_mux/subscription_state.h`): \n   - `handleResponse()`: Processes responses and generates UpdateAck objects\n   - `getNextRequestWithAck()`: Adds ACK information to the next discovery request\n   - `handleBadResponse()`: Converts ACK to NACK when validation fails\n\n## Proto Definitions\nThe ADS service is defined in `api/envoy/service/discovery/v3/ads.proto` with two main RPCs:\n- `StreamAggregatedResources`: Bi-directional streaming of DiscoveryRequest/Response\n- `DeltaAggregatedResources`: Bi-directional streaming of DeltaDiscoveryRequest/Response\n\nThe discovery messages are defined in `api/envoy/service/discovery/v3/discovery.proto` and include the AggregatedDiscoveryService gRPC service definition.\n\n## Key Data Flow\n1. Client creates watches for resources via `addWatch()`\n2. `GrpcMux` multiplexes watch interests across multiple resource types\n3. Subscription state (Delta or SoTW) generates appropriate discovery requests\n4. `GrpcStream` sends requests and receives responses from the management server\n5. Responses are processed by subscription state, triggering ACK/NACK generation\n6. ACKs/NACKs are queued in `PausableAckQueue` and sent with next requests\n7. Updates are delivered to watchers via callbacks"
}

